TI  - The nexus of market pressure, digital-mindset, co-opetition intensity and analytics in the supply chain context
T2  - TOTAL QUALITY MANAGEMENT & BUSINESS EXCELLENCE
AB  - Institutional theory posits that organizations are influenced by external pressures that shape strategic behavior and innovation adoption. Within this framework, we investigate how market competitive pressure drives the dynamics of co-opetition, the use of analytics, and innovation. We further examine how a digital-first mindset and co-opetition intensity moderate these relationships in the context of supply chains. Drawing on survey data from organizations in the United Arab Emirates' food and manufacturing sector, we find that competitive pressure compels organizations to adopt co-opetitive strategies and integrate analytics tools into their operations. Results also reveal that supply chain analytics significantly enhances supply chain innovation. Moreover, when organizations are faced with increased competitive pressure, a digital-first mindset increases their tendency to use analytics tools, which further results in innovation. While co-opetition intensity diminished the impact of supply chain co-opetition on analytics adoption, indicating that the adoption of analytics was lower under conditions of high co-opetition intensity. Implications for theory and practice are offered.
